<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TolE082">
<l>makarat toṭarmoḻi mayaṅkutal varainta</l>
<l>ṉakarat toṭarmoḻi yoṉpaḵ teṉpa</l>
<l>pukaraṟak kiḷanta vaḵṟiṇai mēṉa</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>It is said that there are nine words which belong</l>
<l>without doubt to the non-personal gender in which</l>
<l><foreign xml:lang="ta">ṉ</foreign> occurs finally without having the chance</l>
<l>of being substituted by <foreign xml:lang="ta">m</foreign>.<note
              place="foot">This means, in other words, that in all but these nine items, <foreign
                xml:lang="ta">-m</foreign> alternated with <foreign xml:lang="ta">-ṉ</foreign> in <foreign
                xml:lang="ta">aẖṟiṇai</foreign> (non-personal, neuter) nouns. Among the nine given by <foreign xml:lang="ta">Iḷam.</foreign> are
          words like <foreign xml:lang="ta">ekiṇ</foreign> ' swan ', <foreign xml:lang="ta">kuyiṉ</foreign>
          ' cloud ', <foreign xml:lang="ta">puḻaṉ</foreign> ' tube '.</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
